edit gf-elm-left gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-lg gf-elm-left-xs gf_gs-text-paragraph-1" data-gemlang="en" data-exc="" data-lt-tmp-id="lt-713018" spellcheck="false" data-gramm="false"><p></p><ul><li>Pain at the top of the knee when squatting could be coming from the patella, anterior knee capsule tightness, or the quadriceps tendon.</li><li>Pain behind the knee when squatting could be stemming from a Baker's cyst, posterior capsule tightness, or hamstring tendonitis.</li><li>Knee soreness after doing squats is very common, and it is usually a sign of increased fatigue and tissue sensitivity. Soreness after a squat workout does not typically indicate anything serious. Possible causes of soreness can range from a simple muscle strain or tendonitis to some kind of arthritis.</li><li>Tightness in knee area when squatting can occur as a result of overuse, injury, or age-related wear and tear.</li><li>Sharp pain in knees when squatting occurs mostly when there is an acute injury to the knee structure, or if you are new to squats and your tissues’ tolerance for this movement is limited.&nbsp;</li></ul><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p></div></div><div data-label="Image" data-key="image" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1679992910915" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-image" data-ver="1.0" data-id="1679992910915" data-resolution="3000x3000"><div class="elm gf-elm-center gf_elm-left-xs gf-elm-center-md gf-elm-center-sm gf-elm-center-xs gf-elm-center-lg" data-exc=""><img src="https://ucarecdn.com/76bace7c-e550-4c58-8057-f8df592fd123/-/format/auto/-/preview/3000x3000/-/quality/lighter/WBCM-Heavy-Fron-Squat.jpg" alt="WBCM the man performing squat with heavy bar" class="gf_image" data-gemlang="en" width="1200" height="800" data-width="100%" data-height="auto" title="WBCM the man performing squat with heavy bar" natural-width="1200" natural-height="800"></div></div><div data-label="Text Block" data-key="text-block" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1679992872465" class="ele